Framework Module: Space/RF Segment Assessments
Author: Michael Watson

1. Executive Summary
This document outlines the standard operating procedure (SOP) for conducting Reconnaissance, Scanning, and Enumeration against satellite infrastructure. Unlike terrestrial TCP/IP networks, orbital engagements require a bifurcated approach targeting both the Space Segment (the physical satellite and RF links) and the Ground Segment (terrestrial control servers and user terminals).

2. Phase 1: Reconnaissance (Intelligence Gathering)
The objective of this phase is passive data collection. Before any RF equipment is powered on, we must map the target's orbital mechanics, frequency allocations, and ground infrastructure.

2.1. Orbital Mechanics & Targeting
To intercept signals, we must know exactly when and where the satellite will be in the sky relative to our collection ground station.

TLE (Two-Line Element) Tracking: Utilize sources like Space-Track.org or Celestrak to pull the target's TLE data.
Propagation Modeling: Input TLE data into tracking software (e.g., Gpredict, Orbitron) to calculate exact pass times, elevation, and azimuth for our antenna arrays.
2.2. Frequency & Protocol OSINT
Satellites operate on highly regulated frequencies. We rely on open-source intelligence to find our "entry points."

Regulatory Databases: Query ITU (International Telecommunication Union) and FCC OET databases for the target's frequency filings, bandwidth, and emission designators.
Academic & Hobbyist Networks: Leverage platforms like SatNOGS (Satellite Networked Open Ground Station) to identify known downlink frequencies, baud rates, and modulation schemes (e.g., BPSK, QPSK).
Documentation Leaks: Search for vendor manuals or academic papers detailing the target's framing protocol (most commonly CCSDS - Consultative Committee for Space Data Systems).
2.3. Ground Segment Mapping
The easiest way to compromise a satellite is often through its terrestrial controllers.

ASN Mapping: Identify ASNs belonging to the satellite operator or their contracted ground station providers (e.g., KSAT, AWS Ground Station).
Passive IP Discovery: Use Shodan, Censys, and DNS mapping to find exposed telemetry dashboards, C2 (Command & Control) servers, or VPN endpoints related to the operator.
3. Phase 2: Scanning & Enumeration
This phase bridges the gap between passive listening and active mapping of the target's internal structures.

3.1. RF Spectrum Scanning (The "Space Nmap")
Instead of sweeping IP addresses, we sweep radio frequencies to identify active data channels during a satellite pass.

Hardware: SDRs (Software Defined Radios) capable of wideband reception (e.g., HackRF One, USRP) paired with automated tracking antennas (Yagi or Parabolic).
Waterfall Analysis: Use SDR# or GNU Radio to record the baseband RF data (IQ files) during a pass. We scan the waterfall for Doppler-shifted signals indicative of orbital telemetry.
Demodulation: Pipe the raw RF data through decoders (like GNU Radio flowgraphs or Universal Radio Hacker) to convert analog radio waves into a binary stream.
3.2. Space "Port" Enumeration (CCSDS APID Mapping)
Satellites do not use TCP/UDP ports. Instead, if the satellite uses CCSDS protocols, data is routed using APIDs (Application Process Identifiers).

APID Discovery: Write custom Python scripts to parse the decoded binary frames and extract header data.
Endpoint Mapping: By observing which APIDs are active, we can enumerate the satellite's internal subsystems (e.g., APID 10 might be battery telemetry, APID 50 might be the payload sensor, APID 0 is often the command interface). This is the exact equivalent of finding open ports on a server.
3.3. Ground Segment Active Scanning
While the RF team handles the Space Segment, the network team engages the Ground Segment using traditional methodologies.

Targeted Scanning: Execute nmap and masscan against identified terrestrial ground station IP ranges.
Service Enumeration: Look for specialized control software ports, exposed database ports (often used for telemetry archiving), and insecure management web interfaces.
4. Operational Guardrails & Rules of Engagement
Receive-Only Constraint: During initial scanning, all SDRs MUST be configured for receive-only (RX). Transmitting (TX) without licensing on satellite frequencies is a violation of federal and international law.
IoT/Microcontroller Limits: Micro-tools like the Flipper Zero are out of scope for direct RF scanning due to frequency mismatch (Sub-GHz vs. GHz) and insufficient DSP (Digital Signal Processing) power. Stick to dedicated SDRs.
